Marsico Nuovo, Basilicate, Italy":"Marsico Nuovo, Basilicata, Italien"},"nl":{"ABT 1198–from 1246 to 1286":"circa 1198–van 1246 to 1286","1198–1286":"1198–1286","1185–1248":"1185–1248","1212–1246":"1212–1246","1229–1286":"1229–1286","1172–Male":"1172–Overleden","1175–Female":"1175–Overleden","1248":"1248","ABT 1198":"circa 1198","1246":"1246","from 1246 to 1286":"van 1246 to 1286","1212":"1212","1286":"1286","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","<1212>":"1212","1172":"1172","1229":"1229","Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italië","San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italië","<Of Castello, Di Roccasecca, Frosinone, Italy>":"Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italië","Marsico Nuovo, Basilicate, Italy":"Marsico Nuovo, Basilicata, Italië"},"en":{"ABT 1198–from 1246 to 1286":"about 1198–from 1246 to 1286","1198–1286":"1198–1286","1185–1248":"1185–1248","1212–1246":"1212–1246","1229–1286":"1229–1286","1172–Male":"1172–Deceased","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1248":"1248","ABT 1198":"about 1198","1246":"1246","from 1246 to 1286":"from 1246 to 1286","1212":"1212","1286":"1286","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","<1212>":"1212","1172":"1172","1229":"1229","Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italy","San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italy","<Of Castello, Di Roccasecca, Frosinone, Italy>":"Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Italy","Marsico Nuovo, Basilicate, Italy":"Marsico Nuovo, Basilicata, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"di","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Tomasso","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenic, Guido.","Italian: from a variant of the personal name <i>Tommaso</i>, an equivalent of   Thomas  . Compare   Di Tomasso  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomas","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."]},{"name":"Masso","meanings":["‘Correct man’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Tomasso Medania, di Count de Marsico was born about 1198, in San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italy, his father, Don Guglielmo di Medamia e San Severino, was 28 and his mother, Donna Maria di San Severino, was 25. He had at least 2 sons with PERNA DE  MORRA. He died from 1246 to 1286, in Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italy."},"et":{"ABT 1198–from 1246 to 1286":"umbes 1198–1246 kuni 1286","1198–1286":"1198–1286","1185–1248":"1185–1248","1212–1246":"1212–1246","1229–1286":"1229–1286","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1248":"1248","ABT 1198":"umbes 1198","1246":"1246","from 1246 to 1286":"1246 kuni 1286","1212":"1212","1286":"1286","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","<1212>":"1212","1172":"1172","1229":"1229","Scala, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"Scala, Salerno, Campania, Itaalia","San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Italia":"San Severino, Celle di Bulgheria, Salerno, Campania, Itaalia","<Of Castello, Di Roccasecca, Frosinone, Italy>":"Roccasecca, Frosinone, Lazio, Itaalia","Marsico Nuovo, Basilicate, Italy":"Marsico Nuovo, Basilicata, Itaalia"},"fi":{"ABT 1198–from 1246 to 1286":"noin 1198–vuodesta 1246 vuoteen 1286","1198–1286":"1198–1286","1185–1248":"1185–1248","1212–1246":"1212–1246","1229–1286":"1229–1286","1172–Male":"1172–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut